{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_lily_ver01/data/sn78002169/00279558868/1945090701/0073.xml":{"full_text":"FORECAST 4 /ffff Served By^Leaaed Wires\n\u00a7ggH Humtttgtrot Mnrmttg mar \"Hg:\n^778^N0.259. WILMINGTON, N.'c., FRIDAY, SEPTEMBER 7, 1945 ESTABLISHED 1867\nPEARL HARBOR\nPROBE VOTED\nby JOHN L. CUTTER\nited Press Staff Correspondent\nWASHINGTON. Sept. 6 The\nsenate today voted unanimously\nf a \u2018'searching\u201d Congressional\ninvestigation of the Pearl Harbor\nalter and President Truman\nd he supported the administra\ntion-sponsored proposal in order to\nobtain the whole truth and nothing\nhut the truth.\nMr Truman told a news confer\nence 'a few hours after the Senate\nlion that Congress would have\n1 right to all testimony avail\nhie This was in reply to a ques\ntion whether he thought Congress\nould get portions of the Army\nKavv reports which were deleted\nwhen they were made public last\n\"lie Senate vote came on a reso\n,,.tion bv Democratic leader Alben\nw Barkley of Kentucky who,\nstealing a march on the Republi\ncans formally proposed a non-po\n,itical non-partisan inquiry by a\nspecial 10-man Senate-House com\n\"'speaker Sam Rayburn of Texas\nsaid the House would consider the\nmeasure Monday or Tuesday.\nQuick concurrence is expected.\nBarkley told the Senate that Mr.\nTruman not only approved his res\nolution \u201cbut urged that 1 not be\ndissuaded by any reason.\u2019*\nMr. Truman was asked whether\nhe thought the Army and Navy\nPearl Harbor reports did not give\nthe whole story. He replied that\nall he knew was what he saw in\nthe newspapers and that, while he\nwas satisfied with the reports, not\neverybody felt the same way.\nBarkely\u2019s maneuver was a sur\nprise inasmuch as the impetus for\nan inquiry had come largely from\nthe Republican side, with the Dem\nocratic leadership remaining com\nparatively quiet.\nHis measure, which would pro\nvide $25,000 for the inquiry, calls\nfor immediate creation of a joint\ncommittee consisting of five Sen\nate and five House members who\nwould delve into all phases of the\ndisaster and report their findings\nto Congress by next Jan. 3.\nFranco Bows lo Allies;\nSoldiers Leave Tangiers\nINS TO HONOR\nNHHS WILDCATS\n1945 Squad Will Be Ban\nquet Guests Of Club\nOn October 3\nThe annual banquet for mem\nbers of the New Hanover High\nschool football team will be held\nMonday night, October 3, sponsor\ned by the Lions\u2019 club at the high\nschool cafeteria, according to an\nannouncement at the club s week\nly meeting yesterday. _\nFollowing an informal discussion\nj recently between Lion Walter E.\nYcpp, in charge of arrangements\nfor the occasion, and Coaches Leon\nBrogden and Tom Davis, it was\ndecided that the banquet would be\nmore timely in toe beginning of\nthe season rather than at the close\nof the season. The high school\ncoaches appeared before the\nLions\u2019 club and pressed members\nfor their support of the team this\nyear, and sought the encourage\nment of the entire community for\nthe football team.\nA vote of thanks for cooperation\nin the Lions\u2019 club program to aid\nthe blind and visually handicapped\nin New Hanover county was ex\ntended to Wilmington merchants\nat yesterday\u2019s meeting.\nMany merchants have placed\nchewing gum machines in thqjr\nplaces of business, which bring the\nLions\u2019 club an average of $100 a\nj month, according to the report of\nthe Major Activities Committee\nyesterday. This fund is turned over\nto the aid-to-the-blind program.\nM'Keen Maffitt, chairman of the\nspecial committee, reported that\nthe Lions\u2019 club had furnished ten\npairs of glasses to visually handi\ncapped children within the county\nlast mnnth\nThe Major Activities Committee\nreported yesterday that plans were\nunderway for the Wilmington club\nto sponsor a new club at Leland.\nWilmington Lions paid their re\nspects to the Rev. James Lawson,\nfellow member, who is planning\nto leave the City.\nThe Rev, Sanky Lee Blanton\nWas welcomed back to the club\nafter a long period of inactivity,\ncaused by illness.\nWorshippers To Handle\nSnakes At Funeral\nCHATTANOOGA, Tenn., Sept. 6.\n\u2014<U.R) -Five rattlesnakes, includ\ning the one which caused the\ndeath of Preacher Lewis F. Ford,\nwill be handled at his funeral Sat\nurday at the Dolly Pond Church of\nGod, it was learned today.\nThe snake, which killed Ford at\na meeting of the faith healers\nMonday, has been kept in his fam\nily s home since then, members\nrefusing to kill it because it *was a\n\u201cgood snake.\nIt was not known whether Mrs.\nFord would handle the snake at\nthe funeral.\nWest Point, Annapolis\nTo Get Japanese Swords\nYokohama, Sept. 6.\u2014 oj.p)\nGen. Douglas MacArthur announ\ncea today that the sword whicl\nJapanese Lt. Gen. Tomoyuk\nYamashita surrendered in the Phi\nuppines would be sent to the FJnit\nStates Military Academy a\nWest Point and that the sword o\nlce Adm. Denshichi Okuchi, com\n'handing Japanese Naval force\nK 'he Philippines, would be sen\nCl the United States Naval Acade\nay at Annapolis.\nV\nTANGIERS, Sept. 6- (U.R) \u2014The\nlast Spanish troops left this Inter\nnational Zone in 40 trucks today\nas Gen. Francisco Franco yielded\nto an Allied demand that Spanish\noccupation end. Most of the Span\nish troops had been withdrawn\ngradually over a period of several\nmonths.\nThis little city on the northeast\ncoast of Africa was in a complete\nstate of confusion as result of the\ndecisions taken at the Tangier con\nference in Paris and there were\nseveral protests at the Allied de\ncision to take over the Internation\nal Zone.\nSeme circles point out that Span\nish rights here have nothing to do\nwith who governs Spain but said\nthese rights are those of the Span\nish people.\nMoors who form a large percen\ntage of the population are equally\nupset at the Paris decisions and\nsay the city forms an integral part\nof the Moroccan empire. No agree\nments should be reached concern\ning it without participation of\nMoorish representatives, they said.\nIn this connection it was re\ncalled that the Musulman Nation\nalist party telegraphed the Ameri\ncan and British governments,\nclearly expressing Mussulman op\nposition to the return of the old\nregime with its clear French pre\nponderance.\nThe general impression was that\nno important changes would occur\nimmediately but the Moorish ele\nment was particularly outspoken\nin its criticism of the presence of\nRussia at the conference. They ex\npressed fear that the presence of\nRussia in Tangiers would make it\na center of Communist propagan\nda with consequent harm to Mus\nsulman religion.\nBAR ASSOCIATION\nHONORS NEW HEAD\nRALEIGH. N. C., Sept. 6\nA banquet honoring Willis Smith\nof Raleigh, president-nominee of\nthe American Bar Association to\nnight concluded the second day of\na three-day institute for attorneys\nbeing sponsored in connection with\nthe annual meeting of the North\nCarolina Association which opens\ntomorrow.\nSmith was honored at a dinner\nsponsored by the Wake County Bar\nAssociation, in which he holds\nmembership. Informal talks were\nmade by Irving Carlyle, president\nof the State Bar Association, and\nGovernor R. Gregg Cherry.\nThe annual bar meeting will get\nunderway at noon tomorrow with\na luncheon for members and\nguests. Richard E. Thigpen, chair\nman of the executive committee,\nwill preside. Irving Carlyle will\nadress the luncheon on the topic,\n\"Bar and Legal Education.\nHon. John J. Parker of Char\nlotte, senior judge of the Fourth\nCircuit Court of Appeals and wide.\nly endorsed for appointment to the\nU S. Supreme Court, will be the\nspeaker at a banquet tomorrow\nnight concluding the bar meeting.\nFARRAR ATTENDING\nW. P. Farrar of the Farrar\nTranfser and Warehouse Co.\ni will be one of the delegates\nfrom Wilmington attending the\nMotor Carrier\u2019s Association\nI annual convention to be held at\nt Ilyrtle Beach, S. C. today.\nGovernor R. Gregg Cherry of\n5 North Carolina and Ransom J.\nt Williams Governor of South\nCarolina will speak at the an\nnual affair.\nVice Admiral McCain ^p I\nDies In Cal\u2019\n-#^J\nSAN DIEGO, Ca\u2019 JV A*\n\u2014(A>)\u2014Vice Admir >k \u00bbfs\u2019\u2019 <S\nney McCain, 6\u2019 \u2018y\nof the famous q* .e\nNo. 38, died ick\nat his horn' joro\nnado tonight.\nAdmiral McU id five\nmembers of his sia. .lew here\nyesterday after taking part in\nsurrender ceremonies in Tokyo\nBay.\nEarly today a Navy physi\ncian reported the Admiral was\nworn out from the strain of\nthe past four months\u2019 ac\ntivities directing his task force,\nand that he was suffering from\na slight cold.\nMcCain\u2019s wife and the physi\ncian were at the Admiral\u2019s\nside when he died.\nU. S. PLANES WILL\nFERRY CHINESE\nFirst Contingent Of 80,\n000 Leave For Occu\npation Duty\nCHUNGKING, Sept. 6.-UP)\u2014U.\n3. transport planes, carrying out\nthe greatest airborne movement ol\n;roops in Asiatic history, swarmed\niway today with additional coni'\ngents of the 80,000 Chinese troops\nwho will be flown to reoccupy Nan\nking, Shanghai and other cities of\nChina\u2019s coastal providences.\nThe entire operation of ferrying\ntroops and their equipment is ex\npected to take 40 days, American\nheadquarters said.\nThe fleet took off from Chihkiang\ntoday with units of the crack\nChinese Sixth Army on the 650\nmile flight to Nanking, pre-war\ncapital where Japan\u2019s formal sur\nrender in tnis theater will be sign\ned, possibly on Sunday.\nSome Chinese forces were flown\nto Nanking yesterday, but today\u2019s\noperation marked the official begin\nning of what was described by ex\nperts as the most complex airborne\nmovement of troops ever undertak\nen.\nThe Chinese 94th Army waited at\nLiuchow in Kwangsi province for\nthe 900-mile flight to Shanghai,\nChina\u2019s greatest city. This move\nment is expected to start Sunday.\nThe bulk of Chinese forces were\ndeployed in the Liuchow and Chih\nkiang areas for a drive against Can\nton when the Japanese suddenly\ncapitulated.\nKUHN DEPORTATION\nORDERED BY FEDERAL\nBOA RDOF INQUIRY\nWASHINGTON, Sept. 6-OJ.R)\u2014At\ntorney General Tom Clark today\nordered the deportation to Ger\nmany of Fritz Julius Kuhn, former\nleader of the German American\nBund.\nKuhn is now at Ellis Island,\nN. Y., and will probably be placed\naboard the S. S. Antioch Victory,\nwhich sails next week, the an\nnouncement said.\nClark said Kuhn, is being deport\ned because he is \"dangerous to\nthe public peace and safety of the\nUnited States because he has ad\nhered to the government of Ger\nmany and to the National socialist\nprinciples thereof.\u201d\nKuhn was brought from an alien\nenemy camp at Fort Stanton,\nN. M., last week where he had\nbeen interned. He was given a\nhearing on Tuesday by a special\nthree-man board appointed by the\nAttorney General. The board rec\nommended repatriation\nPullman Reservations\nNow Possible 14 Days\nMEMPHIS, Sept. 6.-(\u00a3>)\u2014 Pull\nman reservations may be made\n14 days in advance beginning Mon\nday, Assistant General Passenger\nAgent John C. Bland of the South\nern Railway system said tonight.\nBland said he had been inform\ned by a Southern Railway spokes\nman at Washington that the office\nof Defense Transportation would\nlengthen the present five-day per\niod to 14 for Pullman reservations\nafter Sunday.\nMacArthur To Unfurl U. S. Flag\nOver Japanese Capital Today;\nTruman Submits Postwar Plans\nPresident\nSends Long\nStatement\n21-POINT PROGRAM\nDirective Cover* Wide\nRange Of Subjects\nFor Consideration\nBy JAMES C. AUSTIN\nUnited Press Staff Correspondent\nWASHINGTON, Sept. 6.\u2014(U.R)\u2014\npresident Truman today submitted\nto the first peacetime Congress in\nfour years a post-war economic\ncharter designed to ease the bur\nden of reconversion for govern\nment, industry, labor, agriculture,\nthe returning war veteran and the\nordinary citizen.\nHis first major post-war mes\nsage was a document of 19,000\nwords. It placed squarely in the\nlaps of the House and Senate a 21\npoint directive to legislate im\nprovements or changes in the tax\nset-up, selective service, congres\nsional salaries, unemployment\ncompensation, full employment,\nand other problems Intimately con\ncerned with the transition from war\nto peace.\nThe message was read to sparse\nly-occupied chambers in both hous\nes by clerks, and first reaction to it\nwas mixed. Mr. Truman made only\none reference to the far-reaching\ndocument his afternoon press\nconference. That was in response to\na question whether he would care\nto make a budget estimate based\nupon his new program. He replied j\nthat no, he could not make such an j\nestimate.\n\u201cThe process of reconversion will\nbe a complicated and difficult one,\u201d\nhe said. \u201cThe general line of ap\nproach is to achieve as full peace\ntime production and employment as\npossible in the most efficient man\n__\nner.\n(Continued on Page 2; Col. 1)\nOFFICERS POINT\nSCORE LOWERED\nWASHINGTON, Sept. 6\u2014CU.R)\u2014'The\nWar Department today established\na new discharge point system for\ncommissioned officers which will\nreturn some 600,000 of its 800,000\nReserve Officers to civilian life by\nnext July 1.\nIt estimated that 200,000 officers\nwill be immediately eligible for\ndischarge under critical point\nscores to be computed on the same\nbasis as those for enlisted men.\nThe officer scores:\nColonels, Lieutenant Colonels\nand Majors\u2014100.\nCaptains and First and Second\nLieutenants\u201485.\nWarrant and Flight Officers\u2014\n80.\nNurses\u201465.\nWAC officers of all grades\u201444.\nPhysical therapists and dieti\ntians\u201441.\nNo provision was made for the\nrelease of general officers\u2014Briga\ndier Generals and above.\nThe system applies to all arms\nand services within the Army but\nprovides that officers with lower\nscores may be released for the\nconvenience of the government\nwhere there are no suitable assign\nments for them. This means that\nthe Army Air Forces will continue\nits recently announced special\npoint plan for discharge of officers\nwith lower point scores.\nuinVllTS tSlArt\nTHROUGH TUNNEL\nCANNON CITY, Colo., Sept. 6\u2014\n(U.R)\u2014Three convicts escaped from\nColorado Penitentiary today after\na two-hour battle with guards in\na tunnel under the prison walls\u2014\nand then showed up unexpectedly\ninside the walls again when roll\ncall was taken several hours later.\nPrison officials frankly admitted\nthat they did not know which three\nof the 1,025 inmates in the peniten\ntiary had made the break. It was\nbelieved that the fugitives, once\noustide the prison walls, realized\nthat the odds were against them\nand decided to join a group of con\nvicts working beyond the walls.\nWith this group, they apparently\nmarched back through the gates\nand were present at roll call.\nTRUMAN NOMINATES\nPAUL V. McNUTT FOR\nPHILLIPINES POST\nWASHINGTON, Sept. 6- .(U.R)\nPresident Truman sent to the Sen\nate today the nomination of Paul\nV. McNutt to serve again as High\nCommissioner to the Phillipines\nand that his job would be to speed\nrecovery df the islands so that in\ndependence may be restored as\nrapidly as possible.\nMcNutt, whose political promin\nence has faded since he was an\naspirant for the presidency in 1940,\nwill go to Manila as soon as he\nis confirmed for the $18,0Q0-a-yeai\npost. Mr. Truman said that the\nUnited States intends to do what\never is necessary to put the Philip\npines back on their feet, and thal\nlegislation in that direction is an\nticipated.\nByrnes And Wife Off For England j\nSecretary of State James F. Byrnes and his wife stand at the\ngangplank of the British liner Queen Elizabeth in New York, ready to\ngo aboard on their trip to England. Secretary Byrnes will attend the.\nforthcoming five-power council of Allied foreign ministers in London,\ncalled to discuss peace terms for Germany, Italy and Japan.\nTruman Speech Highlights\nWASHINGTON, Sept. 6.\u2014(U.R)\n\u2014Highlights of President Tru\nman\u2019s message to congress on\nthe problems of reconversion\nto peace-time:\nCongress reconvenes at a\ntime of great emergency. It\nis an emergency about which,\nhowever, we need have no\nundue fear if we exercise the\nsame energy, foresight and\nwisdom as we did in carry\nin on the war and winning\nthis victory.\nThe process of reconversion\nwill be complicated and diffi\ncult. The general line of ap\nproach is to achieve as full\npeace-time production and em\nployment as possible in the\nmost efficient and speedy\nmanner.\nDisplaced war workers can\nnot find jobs until industry\nhas been regeared and made\nready to produce peace-time\ngoods. During this lag the\ngovernment must provide help.\nDuring the months that lie\nahead some groups in\nbusiness may be tempted to\nsubstitute a short-range\npolicy designed to secure\nprices high enough to provide\nimmediate profits over and\nabove their temporarily high\ncosts These pressures\nmust be resisted.\nDuring the reconversion\nperiod and as long as short\nages in certain materials\nother than food continue, the\n(Continued on Page Eight; Col. 6)\n15,000 TROOPS\nTO TAKE OVER\nFirst Cavalry Division Will Follow Supreme\nCommander Into Tokyo; 7,000,000\nJaps To Be Disarmed By Oct.\nYOKOHAMA, Friday, Sept. 7.\u2014</P)\u2014General MacArthur at the\nhead of 15,000 troops will unfurl the American flag over the ruins of\nTokyo tomorrow (Friday, U. S. time) signalling a swift occupation of\nJapan.\nWithin a week thereafter TJ. S. soldiers will stand guard In the\nrailway city of Sendai, 190 miles north of the capital ,and a week\nSHRINE TO MEET\nHERE ON NOV. 8\nSudan Temple Accepts\nWilmington Invitation\nFor Fall Ceremonial\nWilmington Shriners will be\nhosts to members of Sudan Temple\nwhen the annual fall ceremonial\nof the Shrine is held here Novem\nber 8, it was decided at New Bern\nyesterday at a regular meeting of\nTemple members.\nThe invitation from local Shrin\ners was extended by Shriner J. E.\nL. Wade, who explained plans for\nthe special program to be carried\nout during the day.\nPotentate J. Edward Allen of\nWarrenton presided at yesterday\u2019s\nmeeting, at which all Sedan offi\ncers, with two exceptions, were\npresent.\nWith the lifting of travel restric\ntions, and the removal of gasoline\nrationing, it is expected that Shrin\ners from all over the State will\nbe present at the ceremonial here.\nThe program probably will con\nsist of a street parade featuring\nnew candidates, bands and drill\nteam; the ceremonial program,\nand a dance that night.\nIt is expected that about 75 can\ndidates will be initiated into\nShrinedom during the day, many\nof whom are servicemen in the\nSoutheast section of the State.\nRecord numbers of new mem\nbers have been taken into the\nTemple this year, 151 being initi\nated at New Bern during the Win\nter ceremonial last January, and\n257 were enrolled at the July meet\ning in Kinston.\nSpring and winter ceremonials\nare held annually, but it is not\nthe custom of the Temple to hold\nfall ceremonials every year. How\never, one took place last year at\nGoldsboro, and in 1943 the fall cer\nemony took place at Wilmington.\nSCHOOLBOY MURDERS\nLITTLE GIRL; HEAD\nCRUSHED BY ROCKS\nSOUTH FORK, PA., Sept. 6\n(\u00a3)\u2014Bright-eyed three-year-old Phil\nlis Jean Epperson is dead, and a\nnine-year-old schoolboy has calm\nly admitted, authorities said to\nday, that he pounded her with\nrocks, but that he did not mean\nto kill her.\nThe little girl\u2014her daddy is a\nsoldier in the Philippines was\nfound on an embankment along\nthe rocky bed of the Little Cone\nmaugh river last night. Her head\nhad been crushed.\nSgt. Vincent Bunch of the State\nPolice, said the boy signed a sten\nographic statement of his story\nand that a murder charge will be\nfiled against him.\nFiremen, searching for Phyllis\nwhen she failed to come home aft\ner dark, discovered her body near\nthe rocky creek bed.\nState Police and sheriff\u2019s offi\ncers went to the home of the boy,\na neighbor, and found him sleep\ning peacefully with his brother.\nAssistant district attorney Jack\nBennett described it as apparently\na \"sex case.\u201d\nCzech\u2019s Hang First War\nCriminal In Fast Time\nPRAGUE, CZECHOSLOVAKIA,\nSept. 6\u2014(U.R)\u2014Dr. Joseph Pfitzner,\ndeputy mayor of Prague during\nthe German occupation, was hang\ned today, 2 1-2 hours after he was\nconvicted of treason in Czechoslo\nvakia\u2019s first War Criminal trial.\nThe two-day trial and the prompl\nexecution of the death sentence\nwere expected to set the precedenl\nfor similar justice in the case oj\nKarl Herman Frank, Nazi over\nlord of Czechoslovakia, who is No.\n1 on this country\u2019s War Criminal\nlist.\n\nshu\u2019s west coast and northernmost\nshores.\nCombat patrols yesterday began\npoking through the rubble that air\nonslaughts left of once-great Tokyo,\nwhich only a few weeks ago the\nJapanese were prepared to defend\nto the death with 20 divisions.\nThey were from the vanguards\nof the proud First Cavalry Divi\nsions, veterans of the Southwest\nPacific, first to enter Manila, and\nnow to be granted the honor of be\ning the first into Tokyo\u2014MacArth\nur\u2019s goal.\nThe Allied Supreme Commander\nwill raise over his new quarters in\nTokyo the American flag that flew\nover Washington\u2019s capitol that day\nof Pearl Harbor and which has\nflown in triumph over Rome and\nBerlin, those other Axis capitals\nthat set the world aflame with the\nfires of war.\nAll over Japan\u2019s now-exploded\n'co-prosperity sphere\u201d her arrog*\nant armies were surrendering and\nby mid-October, MacArthur esti\nmated, 7,000,000 Japanese soldiers\nwill be disarmed.\nAt least 3,000,000 of these were\nin the home islands, now marked\nfor occupation by 300,000 to 400,*\n000 American troops as swift as\nconvoys of sea and air can get\nthem ashore. The Fifth Air Force\nand units of the Strategic Air\nForces also will be based in Ja\npan.\nA Japanese naval party was due\nto board a waiting American war\nship today off the northern coast\nof tlm main island of Honshu to\narrange for the surrender Sunday\nof the nearby Ominato naval base\nto Vice Adm. Frank Fletcher's U.S.\nNinth Fleet.\nA big convoy of American troops\nwas ready to land in southern\nKorea, where preliminary airborne\ndetachments were preparing the\nway on the coast 25 miles west of\nSeoul (Keijo), the capital.\nTokyo newspapers reported that\nthe long-subdued Koreans were jp\nrevolt, and the estimated 360,000\nJapanese troops garrisoning the\ncountry were pictured as eagerly\nawaiting the arrival of the Ameri\ncans.\nAn estimated 139,000 Japanese\nSolomons an dother nearby islaVis\nin New Guinea, New Ireland, the\nsurrendered yesterday to the Aus\ntralians and arrangements were be\ning made for an early capitula\ntion in the Celebes, Timor and\nBritish and Dutch Borneo.\n\u201cSUNSHINE GIRL\u201d\nBEATEN TO DEATH\nFAYETTE CITY, PA., Sept. 8\n\u2014(U.P.) \u2014Pretty, red-haired Anna\nElizabeth Dreyer, 17, known as the\n\u201cSunshine Girl\u2019\u2019 because she once\ndefied death and v/on, was found\ntoday in a clump of poison ivy,\nkilled by strangulation and a skull\nfracture.\nHer assailant, for whom a wide\nspread search was on tonight, had\nstripped off Anna\u2019s clothes\u2014all ex\ncept her red and blue party pumps\nand a friendship bracelet on her\nleft arm.\nNearby her beaten body were\nfound her pink slip, white panties,\napron and a navy blue skirt.\nAround her neck were a man\u2019s\nbelt and part of her blue silk\nblouse.\nDoctors were unable to deter\nmine whether she had been crim\ninally assaulted.\nAnna was believed to have been\ndead since last Saturday morning.\nDr. W. R. Vernon, of Perryopolos,\nwho performed an autopsy said\ndeath was caused by strangulation\nand a skull fracture.\nThe girl, one of the most popular\nin this small community, was\nknown by almost everyone because\nof her valiant fight three years\nago in overcoming a serious ill\nness.\nAmerican Intelligence Agents Frustrate Plot\nOf German Saboteurs To Blow Up U. S. Quarters\nFRANKFURT, Sept. 6\u2014 (U.R)\nAmerican counter intelligence\nagents have smashed Germany\u2019s\nfirst underground resistance ring,\narresting the ringleader and 40\nother saboteurs and capturing\n1,200 pounds of dynamite, it was\ndisclosed today.\nLed by a notorious Gestapo offi\ncer from Cologne who worked as\na baker in Weimar, the gang of\nNazi saboteurs planned to blow up\nall United States installations in\nThuringia. Thuringia since then\nhas been taken over by the Rus\nsians.\nA\nThe gang was betrayed by the\n19-year-old blonde mistress of the\nleader and another girl who was\nthe mistress of another of the sa\nboteurs. The girls led the leader\nto a rendezvous, ostensibly for\nlove, and he was captured there.\nThe gang had planned to dyna\nmite vital installations over hun\ndreds of square miles simultan\neously. The members were cap\ntured before they could set off\none blast, and now they are await\ning trial as war' criminals. Mili\ntary law makes them subject to\nthe death penalty if competed.\nAmerican intelligence agents\noad {he \u201cbaker\u201d in Weimar under\nobservation for suspicion of being\nin secret contact with other Ger\nmans early last June, but they\nlacked evidence. Then the blonde\nand her girl friend were arrested,\nand in panic they confessed that\na large underground organization\nwas being made ready to strike\nagainst the Americans.\nThey disclosed that the leader,\nwhose name was withheld by the\ncounter intelligence corps, was\nformerly the commander of secret\npolice in a large German province.\n\nAll other leaders of the gang wer\u00ab\nformer members of the Germar\nintelligence.\nWith the ringleader in custody\nthe Americans began trackin'\ndown other members of the gang\nThey watched a prominent Ger\nman chocolate manufacturer hanc\none of the men a large bundle o:\ndynamite. A raid on the Vnanufac\nturer\u2019s warehouse disclosed mor\u00ab\nthan 1,200 pounds of dynamite com\nplete with detonators and fuse*.","height":"27552","width":"20748"}}
